1
00:00:00,008 --> 00:00:02,826
David was born in Paris, 1748.

2
00:00:02,826 --> 00:00:04,843
His father was killed in a duel

3
00:00:04,843 --> 00:00:06,327
when David was very young,

4
00:00:06,327 --> 00:00:08,979
so already we're starting with violence.

5
00:00:08,979 --> 00:00:11,346
Dead parent before age 10.

6
00:00:11,346 --> 00:00:14,064
Every great origin story has one.

7
00:00:14,064 --> 00:00:16,165
He was raised by well-off uncles

8
00:00:16,165 --> 00:00:18,083
who wanted him to be an architect.

9
00:00:18,083 --> 00:00:19,700
He wanted to paint.

10
00:00:19,700 --> 00:00:20,267
he studied

11
00:00:20,267 --> 00:00:22,918
under a painter named Joseph Marie Vien,

12
00:00:22,918 --> 00:00:23,035
and

13
00:00:23,035 --> 00:00:24,919
he entered the Prix de Rome competition

14
00:00:24,919 --> 00:00:27,937
multiple times through the early 1770s.

15
00:00:27,937 --> 00:00:28,954
He lost.

16
00:00:28,954 --> 00:00:30,988
He entered again, lost again.

17
00:00:30,988 --> 00:00:33,590
He entered a third time, lost again.

18
00:00:33,590 --> 00:00:35,974
And repeated failure broke him.

19
00:00:35,974 --> 00:00:38,392
According to some biographical accounts,

20
00:00:38,392 --> 00:00:40,409
David locked himself in his room

21
00:00:40,409 --> 00:00:41,610
and refused to eat,

22
00:00:41,610 --> 00:00:44,328
convinced his life was over.

23
00:00:44,328 --> 00:00:45,912
The details are murky

24
00:00:45,912 --> 00:00:49,330
and probably exaggerated by later admirers,

25
00:00:49,330 --> 00:00:51,881
but the despair was real.

26
00:00:51,881 --> 00:00:53,499
he was in his mid twenties,

27
00:00:53,499 --> 00:00:55,900
and the one path he staked everything

28
00:00:55,900 --> 00:00:58,467
on kept closing in his face.

29
00:00:58,467 --> 00:01:01,019
He entered again in 1774.

30
00:01:01,019 --> 00:01:02,536
He didn't win.

31
00:01:02,536 --> 00:01:03,603
Just kidding.

32
00:01:03,603 --> 00:01:05,787
He finally got it.

33
00:01:05,787 --> 00:01:08,622
He went to Rome and everything changed.

34
00:01:08,622 --> 00:01:09,789
He arrived in Rome,

35
00:01:09,789 --> 00:01:13,091
and at first wasn't very impressed,

36
00:01:13,091 --> 00:01:15,125
struggling to find his direction.

37
00:01:15,125 --> 00:01:17,826
But soon, the ideas he read about,

38
00:01:17,826 --> 00:01:20,094
especially those of Winckelmann,

39
00:01:20,094 --> 00:01:21,945
the art critic, came to life

40
00:01:21,945 --> 00:01:23,028
in front of him.

41
00:01:23,028 --> 00:01:25,596
He studied ancient sculptures, Raphael

42
00:01:25,596 --> 00:01:27,280
and artists like Caravaggio,

43
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:29,615
spending 5 years learning

44
00:01:29,615 --> 00:01:31,616
and absorbing the art around him.

45
00:01:31,616 --> 00:01:33,316
And when he came back to Paris,

46
00:01:33,316 --> 00:01:35,817
he was a completely different painter.

47
00:01:35,817 --> 00:01:37,652
The loose, colorful style

48
00:01:37,652 --> 00:01:39,936
of his early work was gone.

49
00:01:39,936 --> 00:01:42,787
In its place, moral seriousness,

50
00:01:42,787 --> 00:01:46,239
clean lines, rigid geometry, local colors,

51
00:01:46,239 --> 00:01:49,357
and a restrained palette, muted overall

52
00:01:49,357 --> 00:01:50,941
with sharp accents

53
00:01:50,941 --> 00:01:52,525
guiding the viewer's eyes.

54
00:01:52,525 --> 00:01:55,610
Ancient virtue painted with absolute conviction.

55
00:01:55,610 --> 00:01:57,927
He had become exactly what Winckelmann

56
00:01:57,927 --> 00:01:59,578
the theorist had called for.

57
00:01:59,578 --> 00:02:01,712
He had become neoclassical.

58
00:02:01,712 --> 00:02:04,497
Worth noting, David wasn't alone in this.

59
00:02:04,497 --> 00:02:08,015
Across Europe, artists adopted the neoclassical style

60
00:02:08,015 --> 00:02:11,233
to explore ideas of beauty, harmony,

61
00:02:11,233 --> 00:02:12,400
and timeless order

62
00:02:12,400 --> 00:02:14,501
inspired by ancient Greece and Rome.

63
00:02:14,501 --> 00:02:17,419
Painters used classical myths and historical scenes

64
00:02:17,419 --> 00:02:20,821
to explore heroism, virtue, and human emotion.

65
00:02:20,821 --> 00:02:24,156
Sculptures like Canova focused on elegance

66
00:02:24,156 --> 00:02:27,407
of the human body, calm, idealized forms

67
00:02:27,407 --> 00:02:29,024
in perfect proportions.

68
00:02:29,024 --> 00:02:31,659
The style appeared in mythological paintings,

69
00:02:31,659 --> 00:02:34,627
portraits, architecture, decorative arts.

70
00:02:34,627 --> 00:02:36,261
It became a visual language

71
00:02:36,261 --> 00:02:38,012
of elegance and good taste.

72
00:02:38,012 --> 00:02:39,896
David worked in the same tradition

73
00:02:39,896 --> 00:02:42,030
as all of these artists, but what

74
00:02:42,030 --> 00:02:44,131
he did was charge the style

75
00:02:44,131 --> 00:02:46,399
with moral and political urgency,

76
00:02:46,399 --> 00:02:46,516
and

77
00:02:46,516 --> 00:02:48,616
you can see the difference immediately.

78
00:02:48,616 --> 00:02:50,617
His first big Salon success

79
00:02:50,617 --> 00:02:54,953
was Belisarius Begging for Alms in 1781.

80
00:02:54,953 --> 00:02:58,404
A Roman general, once great, now blind

81
00:02:58,404 --> 00:02:59,872
and begging in the street.

82
00:02:59,872 --> 00:03:01,189
The message?

83
00:03:01,189 --> 00:03:03,740
Even the greatest can be destroyed

84
00:03:03,740 --> 00:03:05,324
by an ungrateful state.

85
00:03:05,324 --> 00:03:06,174
People noticed.

86
00:03:06,174 --> 00:03:06,575
Success

87
00:03:06,575 --> 00:03:08,058
at the Salon made David

88
00:03:08,058 --> 00:03:10,460
a full member of the Académie Royale,

89
00:03:10,460 --> 00:03:12,777
the institute that trained French artists,

90
00:03:12,777 --> 00:03:14,111
set official standards,

91
00:03:14,111 --> 00:03:17,313
and decided what counted as serious painting.

92
00:03:17,313 --> 00:03:18,063
He became

93
00:03:18,063 --> 00:03:20,197
one of its most powerful teachers.

94
00:03:20,197 --> 00:03:22,015
His style, his values,

95
00:03:22,015 --> 00:03:23,982
his way of seeing passed

96
00:03:23,982 --> 00:03:26,317
directly into the next generation.

97
00:03:26,317 --> 00:03:29,001
He wasn't just working within the system,

98
00:03:29,001 --> 00:03:30,318
he was shaping it.

99
00:03:30,318 --> 00:03:31,052
But the painting

100
00:03:31,052 --> 00:03:33,520
that changed everything, the work

101
00:03:33,520 --> 00:03:37,605
that defined Neoclassicism came 3 years later.

102
00:03:37,605 --> 00:03:39,439
This is The Oath of the Horatii.

103
00:03:39,439 --> 00:03:42,891
David painted it in 1784.

104
00:03:42,891 --> 00:03:44,141
Take a moment

105
00:03:44,141 --> 00:03:45,742
and really look at it.

106
00:03:45,742 --> 00:03:47,810
3 brothers, the Horatii,

107
00:03:47,810 --> 00:03:49,043
are swearing an oath.

108
00:03:49,043 --> 00:03:51,044
They're about to fight to the death

109
00:03:51,044 --> 00:03:53,445
for Rome against 3 brothers

110
00:03:53,445 --> 00:03:54,763
for a rival city.

111
00:03:54,763 --> 00:03:56,680
Their father holds the swords.

112
00:03:56,680 --> 00:03:58,414
The brothers reach for them.

113
00:03:58,414 --> 00:04:02,816
Their bodies are taugh, geometric, almost architectural.

114
00:04:02,816 --> 00:04:04,500
They're not individuals.

115
00:04:04,500 --> 00:04:05,751
They're a machine,

116
00:04:05,751 --> 00:04:07,702
a machine built for duty.

117
00:04:07,702 --> 00:04:08,869
Look at the colors.

118
00:04:08,869 --> 00:04:12,237
The brothers wear brighter, more saturated reds.

119
00:04:12,237 --> 00:04:14,788
Your eye goes to them first,

120
00:04:14,788 --> 00:04:16,189
and it's supposed to.

121
00:04:16,189 --> 00:04:17,506
The women on the right

122
00:04:17,506 --> 00:04:20,958
are painted softer, muted tones, blues, grays,

123
00:04:20,958 --> 00:04:21,725
near white.

124
00:04:21,725 --> 00:04:23,209
The color itself tells you

125
00:04:23,209 --> 00:04:24,443
the moral structure

126
00:04:24,443 --> 00:04:27,344
before you even understood what's happening.

127
00:04:27,344 --> 00:04:29,728
Action and duty on the left, grief

128
00:04:29,728 --> 00:04:31,429
and passivity on the right.

129
00:04:31,429 --> 00:04:32,479
The stone background

130
00:04:32,479 --> 00:04:34,530
is all natural browns and grays,

131
00:04:34,530 --> 00:04:36,915
keeping your attention on the figures.

132
00:04:36,915 --> 00:04:39,399
The colors are clean, flat,

133
00:04:39,399 --> 00:04:41,083
and clearly separated.

134
00:04:41,083 --> 00:04:43,351
Every form is clear and deliberate.

135
00:04:43,351 --> 00:04:45,185
Notice also the light.

136
00:04:45,185 --> 00:04:48,937
Harsh, directional, almost theatrical,

137
00:04:48,937 --> 00:04:50,921
like a spotlight on a stage

138
00:04:50,921 --> 00:04:52,322
In the composition,

139
00:04:52,322 --> 00:04:54,456
your eye is drawn to the center,

140
00:04:54,456 --> 00:04:57,224
to the swords, the literal pivot point

141
00:04:57,224 --> 00:04:58,875
between duty and loss.

142
00:04:58,875 --> 00:05:01,126
The whole thing is controlled,

143
00:05:01,126 --> 00:05:04,727
deliberate, organized, the opposite of Rococo

144
00:05:04,727 --> 00:05:06,311
in every possible way.

145
00:05:06,311 --> 00:05:07,528
And then look at the right side

146
00:05:07,528 --> 00:05:09,463
of the painting, the woman.

147
00:05:09,463 --> 00:05:13,131
They're collapsed, weeping, because here's the thing.

148
00:05:13,131 --> 00:05:14,782
One of the Horatii brothers

149
00:05:14,782 --> 00:05:16,032
is married to a woman

150
00:05:16,032 --> 00:05:17,299
from the enemy city.

151
00:05:17,299 --> 00:05:19,184
She's actually the sister

152
00:05:19,184 --> 00:05:20,901
of one of the enemy brothers,

153
00:05:20,901 --> 00:05:23,019
and one of the enemy brothers

154
00:05:23,019 --> 00:05:25,053
is engaged to a Horatii sister.

155
00:05:25,053 --> 00:05:26,704
No matter who wins,

156
00:05:26,704 --> 00:05:29,171
these women lose someone they love.

157
00:05:29,171 --> 00:05:31,189
The men are rigid, vertical,

158
00:05:31,189 --> 00:05:32,673
all straight lines.

159
00:05:32,673 --> 00:05:35,941
The women are curved, soft, crumbling.

160
00:05:35,941 --> 00:05:37,909
Duty on the left, grief

161
00:05:37,909 --> 00:05:39,743
on the right, and the swords

162
00:05:39,743 --> 00:05:40,526
in the center.

163
00:05:40,526 --> 00:05:43,361
The message is brutal and clear.

164
00:05:43,361 --> 00:05:47,279
Duty to the state comes before everything,

165
00:05:47,279 --> 00:05:49,514
before love, before family,

166
00:05:49,514 --> 00:05:51,098
before your own life.

167
00:05:51,098 --> 00:05:52,732
When this painting was exhibited

168
00:05:52,732 --> 00:05:53,632
at the salon,

169
00:05:53,632 --> 00:05:55,483
people wept in front of it.

170
00:05:55,483 --> 00:05:57,734
Not just because it was sad,

171
00:05:57,734 --> 00:05:59,552
because it was powerful.

172
00:05:59,552 --> 00:06:01,369
It felt like a call to action.

173
00:06:01,369 --> 00:06:02,686
And David didn't stop.

174
00:06:02,686 --> 00:06:05,738
In 1780 7, The Death of Socrates.

175
00:06:05,738 --> 00:06:08,389
Socrates, condemned by the Athenian state

176
00:06:08,389 --> 00:06:09,373
for his ideas,

177
00:06:09,373 --> 00:06:09,806
calmly

178
00:06:09,806 --> 00:06:11,890
reaching for the cup of poison

179
00:06:11,890 --> 00:06:14,442
while his students fall apart around him.

180
00:06:14,442 --> 00:06:16,326
The state is killing him,

181
00:06:16,326 --> 00:06:19,294
and he accepts it with perfect calm.

182
00:06:19,294 --> 00:06:20,828
You die for what you believe.

183
00:06:20,828 --> 00:06:23,195
And then, in 1780 9,

184
00:06:23,195 --> 00:06:24,913
the lictors bring to Brutus

185
00:06:24,913 --> 00:06:26,013
the bodies of his sons.

186
00:06:26,013 --> 00:06:28,548
Brutus, the founder of the Roman Republic,

187
00:06:28,548 --> 00:06:30,299
has ordered the execution

188
00:06:30,299 --> 00:06:31,783
of his own sons

189
00:06:31,783 --> 00:06:34,250
for conspiring to restore the monarchy

190
00:06:34,250 --> 00:06:36,685
The bodies are being carried past him.

191
00:06:36,685 --> 00:06:37,885
He doesn't look.

192
00:06:37,885 --> 00:06:39,253
The women scream.

193
00:06:39,253 --> 00:06:40,737
He sits in shadow,

194
00:06:40,737 --> 00:06:43,438
rigid, destroyed, but unbroken.

195
00:06:43,438 --> 00:06:45,772
This painting was displayed at the Salon

196
00:06:45,772 --> 00:06:47,540
just weeks after the storming

197
00:06:47,540 --> 00:06:48,490
of the Bastille.

198
00:06:48,490 --> 00:06:50,258
The Paris prison was attacked

199
00:06:50,258 --> 00:06:52,175
in July 1789,

200
00:06:52,175 --> 00:06:54,926
marked the beginning of the French Revolution.

201
00:06:54,926 --> 00:06:57,211
The story goes that authorities tried

202
00:06:57,211 --> 00:06:58,795
to pull it from the exhibition,

203
00:06:58,795 --> 00:07:00,879
but the crowd demanded it to stay.

204
00:07:00,879 --> 00:07:01,846
whether that happened

205
00:07:01,846 --> 00:07:04,297
exactly as described is debated.

206
00:07:04,297 --> 00:07:05,915
Some historians think

207
00:07:05,915 --> 00:07:07,632
the tale was polished later

208
00:07:07,632 --> 00:07:10,433
to make David seem more heroically embattled.

209
00:07:10,433 --> 00:07:14,318
Regardless, the painting's timing was explosive.

210
00:07:14,318 --> 00:07:15,552
Do you see what's happening?

211
00:07:15,552 --> 00:07:17,803
These aren't just paintings anymore.

212
00:07:17,803 --> 00:07:19,204
A painting about a man

213
00:07:19,204 --> 00:07:20,338
who killed his sons

214
00:07:20,338 --> 00:07:22,872
to protect the Republic, displayed in Paris

215
00:07:22,872 --> 00:07:25,373
in summer of 1789?

216
00:07:25,373 --> 00:07:27,274
That's not art appreciation.

217
00:07:27,274 --> 00:07:29,558
That's a political statement, and

218
00:07:29,558 --> 00:07:31,092
everyone in that room knew it.

219
00:07:31,092 --> 00:07:32,510
David had spent a decade

220
00:07:32,510 --> 00:07:34,210
painting ancient heroes

221
00:07:34,210 --> 00:07:36,562
who sacrificed everything for the state,

222
00:07:36,562 --> 00:07:38,379
and now, in the summer of

223
00:07:38,379 --> 00:07:41,964
1789, the state was being torn apart

224
00:07:41,964 --> 00:07:42,931
and rebuilt.

225
00:07:42,931 --> 00:07:44,082
And David wasn't going

226
00:07:44,082 --> 00:07:45,299
to just paint it,

227
00:07:45,299 --> 00:07:47,466
he was going to join it.

228
00:07:47,466 --> 00:07:49,317
This is where the story goes dark,

229
00:07:49,317 --> 00:07:51,368
and I mean genuinely dark.

230
00:07:51,368 --> 00:07:53,636
Not art world drama dark.

231
00:07:53,636 --> 00:07:55,020
People dying dark.

232
00:07:55,020 --> 00:07:57,621
In 1792, David was elected

233
00:07:57,621 --> 00:08:01,189
to the National Convention, the revolutionary parliament.

234
00:08:01,189 --> 00:08:03,207
He didn't sit with the moderates.

235
00:08:03,207 --> 00:08:04,924
He sat with the Montagrats,

236
00:08:04,924 --> 00:08:07,125
the radicals, the Jacobins.

237
00:08:07,125 --> 00:08:07,792
They were led

238
00:08:07,792 --> 00:08:10,143
by Maximilian Robespierre, the lawyer

239
00:08:10,143 --> 00:08:12,661
who made himself the ideological heart

240
00:08:12,661 --> 00:08:13,611
of the revolution

241
00:08:13,611 --> 00:08:15,079
and who was rapidly becoming

242
00:08:15,079 --> 00:08:16,529
its most feared figure.

243
00:08:16,529 --> 00:08:19,481
And on January twenty-first, seventeen ninety-three,

244
00:08:19,481 --> 00:08:20,381
the day I mentioned

245
00:08:20,381 --> 00:08:21,248
at the beginning,

246
00:08:21,248 --> 00:08:22,048
David voted

247
00:08:22,048 --> 00:08:25,033
for the execution of King Louis XVI.

248
00:08:25,033 --> 00:08:28,385
A painter voted to kill a king.

249
00:08:28,385 --> 00:08:29,802
But he didn't stop there.

250
00:08:29,802 --> 00:08:33,970
David became essentially the revolution's visual authority.

251
00:08:33,970 --> 00:08:37,655
He organized festivals, massive public events meant

252
00:08:37,655 --> 00:08:41,257
to replace Catholic ritual with republican ceremony.

253
00:08:41,257 --> 00:08:43,508
He contributed to the design of uniforms

254
00:08:43,508 --> 00:08:44,892
and public imagery.

255
00:08:44,892 --> 00:08:46,509
He was deeply involved

256
00:08:46,509 --> 00:08:48,894
in shaping what the revolution looked like,

257
00:08:48,894 --> 00:08:51,378
and in a world before photography,

258
00:08:51,378 --> 00:08:52,745
before television,

259
00:08:52,745 --> 00:08:55,380
that meant he had real influence

260
00:08:55,380 --> 00:08:57,364
over what people believed about it.

261
00:08:57,364 --> 00:08:58,815
He was close to Robespierre,

262
00:08:58,815 --> 00:09:00,599
the radical Jacobin leader.

263
00:09:00,599 --> 00:09:01,850
Very close.

264
00:09:01,850 --> 00:09:03,567
He reportedly said to him,

265
00:09:03,567 --> 00:09:05,068
"If you drink hemlock,

266
00:09:05,068 --> 00:09:06,868
I will drink it with you."

267
00:09:06,868 --> 00:09:08,986
That's not a casual friendship.

268
00:09:08,986 --> 00:09:10,020
That's a pact.

269
00:09:10,020 --> 00:09:11,621
He was actively involved

270
00:09:11,621 --> 00:09:13,355
in the revolutionary government,

271
00:09:13,355 --> 00:09:16,073
sitting on the Committee of General Security,

272
00:09:16,073 --> 00:09:17,973
putting his name on documents

273
00:09:17,973 --> 00:09:21,792
that led to people being arrested, tried, and executed.

274
00:09:21,792 --> 00:09:22,125
was

275
00:09:22,125 --> 00:09:23,176
one of many people

276
00:09:23,176 --> 00:09:25,293
who signed, not acting alone,

277
00:09:25,293 --> 00:09:27,111
but consider what that means

278
00:09:27,111 --> 00:09:27,728
for the man

279
00:09:27,728 --> 00:09:29,729
who painted the death of Socrates.

280
00:09:29,729 --> 00:09:31,946
You remember that painting, Socrates

281
00:09:31,946 --> 00:09:33,130
in his last moments,

282
00:09:33,130 --> 00:09:35,398
calmly reaching for the cup of poison

283
00:09:35,398 --> 00:09:37,816
while his students fall apart around him?

284
00:09:37,816 --> 00:09:40,850
Socrates was condemned by the Athenian state

285
00:09:40,850 --> 00:09:43,451
for refusing to abandon his ideas.

286
00:09:43,451 --> 00:09:45,853
That's the subject David chose to paint

287
00:09:45,853 --> 00:09:47,136
and made beautiful,

288
00:09:47,136 --> 00:09:49,254
a man killed by the state.

289
00:09:49,254 --> 00:09:51,505
And now, David was the state.

290
00:09:51,505 --> 00:09:53,339
His name was on the paperwork.

291
00:09:53,339 --> 00:09:55,724
The tension between the ideals he painted

292
00:09:55,724 --> 00:09:58,792
and the reality he served is staggering.

293
00:09:58,792 --> 00:10:01,643
In July 1793, a shocking event

294
00:10:01,643 --> 00:10:04,027
in revolutionary Paris gave rise to

295
00:10:04,027 --> 00:10:06,495
one of the century's most famous paintings.

296
00:10:06,495 --> 00:10:09,430
Jean-Paul Marat was a revolutionary journalist,

297
00:10:09,430 --> 00:10:10,447
a radical.

298
00:10:10,447 --> 00:10:12,048
He had a skin condition

299
00:10:12,048 --> 00:10:13,848
that forced him to spend hours

300
00:10:13,848 --> 00:10:15,566
in a medicinal bath,

301
00:10:15,566 --> 00:10:17,600
where he would write, receive visitors,

302
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:19,117
and conduct business.

303
00:10:19,117 --> 00:10:21,718
On July 13th, 1793,

304
00:10:21,718 --> 00:10:24,370
a young woman named Charlotte Corday

305
00:10:24,370 --> 00:10:26,137
talked her way into his apartment,

306
00:10:26,137 --> 00:10:30,989
claiming to have information about counter-revolutionary plots.

307
00:10:30,989 --> 00:10:32,140
Marat received her

308
00:10:32,140 --> 00:10:33,640
while sitting in his bath.

309
00:10:33,640 --> 00:10:35,208
She pulled out a knife

310
00:10:35,208 --> 00:10:37,192
and stabbed him in the chest.

311
00:10:37,192 --> 00:10:39,160
He died almost immediately.

312
00:10:39,160 --> 00:10:40,210
According to accounts

313
00:10:40,210 --> 00:10:41,611
that have been passed down,

314
00:10:41,611 --> 00:10:44,929
though some historians treat this with caution,

315
00:10:44,929 --> 00:10:46,530
David had visited Marat

316
00:10:46,530 --> 00:10:47,580
the day before.

317
00:10:47,580 --> 00:10:48,630
He knew the bath,

318
00:10:48,630 --> 00:10:50,198
the setup, the man,

319
00:10:50,198 --> 00:10:51,749
and when he heard the news,

320
00:10:51,749 --> 00:10:53,283
he went to work immediately.

321
00:10:53,283 --> 00:10:54,100
Look at it.

322
00:10:54,100 --> 00:10:56,017
Marat is slumped in his bath.

323
00:10:56,017 --> 00:10:57,801
His head is wrapped in a cloth.

324
00:10:57,801 --> 00:11:00,152
His skin is pale, almost glowing.

325
00:11:00,152 --> 00:11:02,570
His face is calm, peaceful.

326
00:11:02,570 --> 00:11:04,204
He looks like he's sleeping.

327
00:11:04,204 --> 00:11:05,872
He looks like Christ

328
00:11:05,872 --> 00:11:07,239
taken down from the cross.

329
00:11:07,239 --> 00:11:08,223
But I'll get to that

330
00:11:08,223 --> 00:11:08,723
in a sec.
